<li id="c67">
  <div class="cx" id="cx50220981">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">I stopped watching TV news in 1984 ...</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1210285/50220981#c67?mode=alone;showrate=1#c67">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>... and ABC was the station I switched off, too. &nbsp;But it could have been any station by that point in my life.</p>
<p>It was the morning after the second Reagan-Mondale debate, and I switched on "ABC World News This Morning" to hear Kathleen Sullivan tell me that the top story of the day was that Reagan's people said Reagan had won the debate and Mondale's people said Mondale had won the debate.</p>
<p>I said, "That's not news," turned off the set, and have not watched network news since. &nbsp;(The only exception I've made was for about half an hour the night of 9/11/01 after I got home from my job in Boston.)</p>
<p>Years later I learned that same debate was identified by the late William Safire as the night the terms "spin" and "spin doctor" were born.</p>

