<p>and eventually cover it in detail? I think it's very important:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.democracynow.org/2013/5/20/geoengineering_can_we_save_the_planetGeoengineering">Can We Save the Planet By Messing With Nature?</a> I still can't calm down after having listened to it.</p>
<p>You know I am driving by the Cato Institute every morning and after Hunter's recent diary about them glorifying the 400 ppm threshold of CO2 emissions, what I heard this morning about how they are again involved in support of "shielding the earth from the sun with a cloud of mirrors in space to deflect sunlight, thus preventing the sun's radiation to the earth and heating it up "too much". &nbsp;</p>
<p>Imagine, on the one hand people try to develop solar energy by putting up solar panel farms capturing the sunlight to generate alternative energy, why at the same time "geoengineering nut-cracks" phantasizing about putting up a shield of mirrors above the clouds to avoid the sun's radiation to reach our earth's surface.<br /></p>
<blockquote>We’re joined now by Clive Hamilton, professor of public ethics at Charles Stuart University in Canberra, Australia. Hamilton’s new book, "Earthmasters: The Dawn of the Age of Climate Engineering," lays out the arguments for and against climate engineering, and reveals the vested interests behind it linking <b>researchers, venture capitalists and corporations.</b></blockquote>
The interview starts at TC 27:51.<br />
Transcript not out yet. I hope that gets some eyes and ears.

